  "market_context": "NQ1! was trading within a defined range. London session swept the range low, establishing a likely bullish bias. New York session then extended higher, taking out the previous day's high as external liquidity before reversing aggressively back into the range.",
  "key_observation": "London swept the sell-side liquidity (range low), signaling continuation higher. New York took the previous day's high (buy-side liquidity), triggering a change in state of delivery and an aggressive reversal back into the range, with low resistance liquidity resting below as the target.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a defined price range on NQ1!, marking the range high (previous day's high) and the most current swing low as the range low.",
    "Step 2: Observed that during London session, price swept out the range low, forming a session low — interpreted as a signal that price was likely to continue higher toward the range high.",
    "Step 3: Watched New York open make an opposing run higher, continuing to take all liquidity from the previous day's high (external buy-side liquidity sweep).",
    "Step 4: Noted an aggressive displacement move out of the previous day's high followed by a reversal back into the range, identifying this as a change in state of delivery (CHoCH).",
    "Step 5: Identified low resistance liquidity (session lows and previous days' lows) resting below within the range as the downside target.",
    "Step 6: Planned a short entry at the change in state of delivery level, with stop above the order block and a 2R target into the low resistance liquidity zone.",
    "Step 7: Confirmed the New York Reversal daily profile on the daily chart — price swept one side of the range (buy-side) and low resistance liquidity was resting on the other side (sell-side) as the continuation target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price did not tag the trader in before moving toward the target; the trade setup was valid but entry was missed. The daily chart confirmed the New York Reversal profile with low resistance liquidity as the continuation target.",
  "lessons": "When London sweeps external sell-side liquidity and New York then sweeps external buy-side liquidity (previous day's high), the resulting change in state of delivery signals a New York Reversal profile. Low resistance liquidity inside the range becomes the high-probability continuation target.",
